    title: 'Do Pre-Tournament Friendlies Actually Tell Us Anything?',
    excerpt:
      'Teams play warm-up matches before a World Cup, and fans read the results like tea leaves. How much do these friendlies really reveal?',
    date: '2026-07-31',
    minutes: 4,
    author: 'The Xaa Desk',
    sections: [
      { h: '', p: [
        'In the weeks before a World Cup, national teams play warm-up friendlies, and fans and pundits pore over the results for clues about who is ready and who is in trouble. But friendlies are a peculiar form of football, and reading too much into them is a classic pre-tournament trap. The honest question is how much they actually tell us.',
        'The answer is: something, but far less than the scorelines suggest.'] },
      { h: 'Why the results mislead', p: [
        'Friendlies are played with different priorities than competitive matches. Coaches experiment with line-ups and tactics, rest key players, and often care more about fitness and combinations than winning. A heavy defeat may hide useful experimentation, and a big win may come against limited opposition or reveal little about tournament readiness. The result is frequently the least informative part.',
        'Treating a warm-up score as a verdict on a team’s chances is a reliable way to be wrong.'] },
      { h: 'What they genuinely show', p: [
        'This does not mean friendlies are worthless. They offer glimpses of fitness, of how new tactical ideas are bedding in, of which combinations look promising, and of the general mood around a squad. Coaches use them to finalise plans and build understanding, and attentive observers can learn about a team’s intended shape and approach even when the result is meaningless.',
        'The value is in the process and the details, not the final score.'] },
      { h: 'Reading them wisely', p: [
        'The sensible approach is to watch friendlies for information rather than judgement: how a team is trying to play, who is being trusted, how fresh ideas look — while holding the results lightly. Many teams that struggled in warm-ups have thrived at tournaments, and vice versa.',
        'As 2026 approaches, enjoy the friendlies for the clues they offer, but resist crowning or condemning anyone on their basis. The real evidence only arrives once the tournament begins.'] },
    ],
